The partial pressure of phosphorus vapor above liquid silicon is complex since phosphorus has three significant gaseous species. As is reported by Schlesinger,[14] vaporizing red or liquid phosphorus forms a gas consisting primarily of P4, which is the predominant form below 973 K (700 °C). Above this temperature, the presence of P2 vapor becomes noticeable and increasingly dominant above 1533 K (1260 °C). At much higher temperatures, monatomic phosphorus vapor begins to appear. Therefore, the partial pressure of phosphorus vapor above liquid silicon is decided by the thermodynamic properties of pP, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
